## Why it matters

When a busy service suddenly floods a downstream database, queue, or third-party API, you get slow queues, timeouts, retries, and sometimes full outages. Backpressure prevents *overload* by making senders respect the receiver's capacity. Without it, spikes ripple through your architecture and cause cascading failures.

**Analogy:** imagine a restaurant kitchen (consumer) and waiters (producers). If waiters keep bringing orders faster than the kitchen can cook, dishes pile up, cooks burn out, and orders get delayed. Backpressure is the head chef signaling the waiters: "Slow down—we can only handle two orders at a time." The system stays healthy and customers get food reliably.

---

## How backpressure works (simple picture)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  Client->>Gateway: request(data)
  Gateway->>Service: forward(data)
  Service->>Downstream: process(data)
  Downstream-->>Service: capacity=low
  Service-->>Gateway: 503/Retry-After or signal
  Gateway-->>Client: 429/Retry-After
  Client-->>Gateway: retry(after)
```

This sequence shows a capacity signal from a busy downstream service propagating back to clients via HTTP status or other signals.

---

## Core patterns for backpressure

- **Push-based with explicit feedback:** consumers send signals (window size, credits) to producers (e.g., TCP windowing, Reactive Streams). Useful when you control both sides.
- **Pull-based:** producers expose pull APIs and consumers ask for data when ready (e.g., Kafka consumers pulling messages). Good when consumers should control throughput.
- **Rate-limit & reject (fast-fail):** overload triggers 429/503 responses with Retry-After; keep queues short and let clients back off.
- **Buffering with bounded queues:** small buffers smooth bursts; when full, apply drop-oldest/drop-newest or backpressure upstream.
- **Adaptive throttling:** dynamic limits based on observed latency, queue depth, or error rate.

---

## Flowchart: producer-consumer with backpressure

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Producer[Producer] -->|send| Buffer[Bounded Buffer]
  Buffer -->|deliver| Consumer[Consumer]
  Consumer -->|when busy| Signal[Backpressure Signal]
  Signal --> Producer
  Buffer -->|full| Reject[Reject/Drop/Respond 429]
```

---

## Before / After: no backpressure vs with backpressure

| Scenario | Pros | Cons | When to Use |
|----------|------|------|-------------|
| **No backpressure** (fire-and-forget) | Simple; minimal coupling | Fast overload, cascading failures, high retries | Very short-lived jobs, highly reliable downstreams
| **With backpressure** (signals, bounded buffers) | Stable under load, predictable latency, graceful degradation | More complex; requires protocol or client cooperation | Production services, public APIs, streaming data pipelines

---

## Practical examples

### 1) HTTP API: Fast-fail and Retry-After
Use a short queue and reject excess requests with 429 or 503 and a Retry-After header. Clients should implement exponential backoff.

```js
// Express example: simple concurrency limiter
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
let inFlight = 0;
const MAX_IN_FLIGHT = 50;

app.post('/process', (req, res) => {
  if (++inFlight > MAX_IN_FLIGHT) {
    inFlight--; // revert
    res.set('Retry-After', '1');
    return res.status(429).send('Too Many Requests');
  }

  doWork(req.body).then(() => {
    inFlight--;
    res.send('ok');
  }).catch(err => {
    inFlight--;
    res.status(500).send('error');
  });
});
```

Clients should back off when they see 429 and respect Retry-After. That prevents the system from accumulating unbounded work.

### 2) Node.js streams: builtin backpressure
Node streams manage backpressure by having writable stream.write() return false when the internal buffer is full; producers should stop producing until the 'drain' event.

```js
const { Readable, Writable } = require('stream');

const fastProducer = new Readable({
  read() {
    for (let i=0;i<1000;i++) {
      if (!this.push(String(i))) return; // push returned false => backpressure
    }
    this.push(null);
  }
});

const slowConsumer = new Writable({
  write(chunk, enc, cb) {
    setTimeout(() => cb(), 10); // slow
  }
});

fastProducer.pipe(slowConsumer); // Node ensures backpressure automatically
```

### 3) Reactive Streams / credit-based
The Reactive Streams spec and many frameworks (Project Reactor, RxJava, Akka Streams) implement a request(n) mechanism—consumers request N items when ready. This is the most explicit and powerful form.

---

## When to use each approach

| Approach | Pros | Cons | When to use |
|---|---:|---|---|
| Push with signals (Reactive Streams) | Tight flow control, low memory | Requires protocol support | Internal services/streams where both sides can change
| Pull (consumer-driven, e.g., Kafka) | Consumers fully control pace | Slightly higher latency | Pub/sub, message processing at scale
| Reject/429 with Retry-After | Simple, stateless, works with any client | Shifts complexity to clients | Public HTTP APIs, microservices with many clients
| Bounded buffer + drop policy | Smooth short bursts | Needs careful policy chosen | Real-time pipelines with burstiness

---

## Common pitfalls

- **Silent drops:** dropping work without telling the producer causes invisible data loss.
- **Infinite buffering:** unbounded queues hide overload and blow up memory.
- **Blind retries:** clients retry aggressively on 5xx/429 without exponential backoff, worsening load.
- **Mixed strategies without coordination:** if producer and consumer use different semantics (push vs pull), signals are ignored.
- **Not measuring the right signals:** using CPU alone can be misleading; measure queue lengths, response latency, and error rates.

---

## Practical checklist to add backpressure to your system

1. Identify choke points (DB, external APIs, CPU-bound services).
2. Add bounded queues/buffers with clear drop/reject policies.
3. Propagate capacity signals: use request(n), 429/503+Retry-After, or custom headers (X-Rate-Limit-Remaining).
4. Implement client-side backoff and jitter.
5. Monitor queue lengths, latencies, and retry storms.
6. Run chaos tests to verify the system degrades gracefully.

---

## TL;DR

Backpressure keeps systems resilient by matching production rate to consumption capacity. Use protocol-level signals (Reactive Streams) when you control both ends, pull models for consumer-driven throughput, and fast-fail + Retry-After for public HTTP endpoints. Avoid infinite buffers and implement client backoff.
